The Iowa data is highly likely to have been collected in 2010 and thus is somewhat old data. 
The max for the YearBuilt column is 2010, and the max for YearRemodAdd is also 2010. With a count of 1460 rows of data, it would be extremely unlikely that not one house was built after 2010 AND that no house had a remodel or addition after 2010.
There's probably some data somewhere to see that there were new homes built after 2010 and there have been remodels after 2010 as well.
If we were using this to train a machine learning model, it wouldn't be very useful as housing trends have changed significantly since then due to various outside influences.
Also, the data can tell us a lot about the past, but can only tell us about a future where the internal and external influences don't change.

There are 2 possible explanations

The most likely is that they stopped building or there is not more room to build in that area.  A new house hasn't gone up in my area in over 50 years.
They either stopped collecting data or data was lost.

In order to find out, we would need to check the area records to get a clear picture.

Hi @michaelzabolocki 
Thank you for using the spike dataset, and I'm very happy that you can reproduce my analysis. I'm having tons of discussions on how to functionally identify these neurons. Doing transcript analysis of excised nucleus from neurons (nucleated patch-clamp, Sather et al., j.physiol 1992, now people call it patch-seq) would be one way to do it. However, the neuronal classification provided by single-cell transcriptomic is different from what classic neurophysiologists understand as neurons. What I tried is to combine extracellular waveform together with fluorescently guided patched-clamped neurons that express a neuronal-like maker DLXi5/6 or alpha-CaMKII, without much success.
I have more data on those spikes, and my idea was to train a network to simply identify organoid types, there're literally tons of things to do.
Thanks for your feedback!
Jose

Sounds very interesting. I know that it is not very specific, but there is a technique called 'MEA-seq' which would allow you to combine MEA data with bulk RNA-seq data. For instance, at 100 days in-vitro, you could record your brain organoids then sequence their RNA. This would provide insight into their genetics and possible neuronal subtypes. Allen Brain have a great patch-seq database from Human Brain data, which you could potentially use for correlation. The possible case solution here would to then combine this with the MEA data, and try to isolate some sort of relationship between the genetic underlying and the extracellular wave patterns. I can see why this is difficult though, as it would still lead you to a similar issue - which is, what exactly correlates with what? These are simply ideas. Maybe you can make something of my rambling here…. 
The fluorescent guided patch-clamping is a good idea. I suppose that didn't work great as (from my experiences atleast) those markers can not be too specific. 
I like the network training approach. 
Best, 
Michael

Hi. Thank you for your comment. I can try explain it.
1) train.columns - return list with columns name (['PassengerId', 'Survived',….]). but i need column names that have at least one gap
2) train.isnull() - return dataframe with same shape as the original, but instead of values there True(empty) or False(not empty)
3) train.isnull().any() - return Series were indexes are column names, values are True(have one or more empty cells in dataframe) or False(have not empty cells)
4) enumerate(train.isnull().any()) - returns on every iteration index(ind)(column number)  and value(x)(True or False)
5) if x is True, then return ind. Then use the index list to get columns name: train.columns[index]
If something isn't clear, tell me about it, i will try to explain or you can try run in this order.

Your evaluate_guess function does not match what Wordle web site itself returns. For example:
evaluate_guess('slime','truss') returns 'NNNMM'. Actual Wordle would only return only one M (yellow) on the first instance of s not on both. So reality would be NNNMN.
Unlikely to make a big difference since most people don't guess double letter words but  FYI.

Alright, so the error you get is 

  ValueError: Length mismatch: Expected axis has 1447 elements, new values have 1168 elements

which is due to this line

  ---> 19 OH_X_test.index = X_train.index


You should use OH_X_test.index = X_test.index to have an actual match ! (X_test & X_train don't have the same amount of rows and thus, don't have the same indexes)
You're going to get quite a few other issues by running the code you wrote afterwards. There's a lot to learn by debugging it. Two lines of code that'll probably help you a lot in that endeavour :

  
  df.isnull().sum() shows the number of null values per feature in your dataframe df
  df[df['feature'].isnull()] shows rows where the 'feature' column is null

Hello Kagglers!
If you enjoyed M5, we would like to invite you to participate in M6, the new financial forecasting competition organized by Spyros Makridakis and his team.
The main goal of the M6 competition is to empirically identify the most appropriate way of forecasting financial (stock and ETF) prices as well as to investigate the connection between the accuracy of such forecasts and the associated returns on investment.  
That said, in the M6 competition you’ll be asked to rank 100 assets in terms of expected percentage returns and determine the weights for investing in these assets (long and/or short positions).
The competition is live and consists of 12 submission periods (one per month), thus covering a full calendar year. However, rankings and prizes will be announced at various points (monthly, quarterly and total).
Currently, the competition is open for a trial run. This trial will help you get familiar with the data and the objectives of the competition, also providing you more time to develop your solutions and receive valuable feedback.  
For more info, continue reading here:
https://mofc.unic.ac.cy/the-m6-competition/
Cheers!
